Special permission bits — SUID, SGID, and sticky.

Beyond the nine read-write-execute bits you learned in module three, there are three special permission bits. They don't get their own column; instead they appear as modifiers sitting in the execute positions of an ls dash-l listing. Let's take them one at a time.

First, SUID, set-user-ID, which is the numeric value four-thousand. When it's set on an executable file, the program runs as the file's owner, not as the user who launched it. The perfect example is slash-usr-bin-passwd. Think about it: a regular user needs to change their own password, which means writing into etc-shadow, but etc-shadow is owned by root and writable by no one else. The solution is that passwd is owned by root and has the SUID bit set, so when you run it, that process runs as root just long enough to update the file. In ls dash-l, SUID shows up as a lowercase s where the owner's execute bit would normally be. Now, SUID is powerful and genuinely dangerous: a bug in a SUID-root program is a direct privilege-escalation hole, letting anyone become root. So systems keep the list of SUID binaries small and carefully audited. You can find them all with find slash, dash-perm, dash-four-thousand, dash-type f.

Second, SGID, set-group-ID, the value two-thousand. On an executable it runs with the file's group, which is rare. But on a directory it's genuinely useful and common: any new file created inside inherits that directory's group, rather than the creator's own primary group. That's the standard recipe for a shared project directory. You chgrp the directory to your team group, then chmod two-seven-seven-five on it, and from then on every file anyone creates there belongs to the team group, so the whole team can collaborate. In ls dash-l, SGID appears as a lowercase s in the group's execute position.

Third, the sticky bit, value one-thousand. On a shared, world-writable directory, it means that only a file's owner, or root, can delete or rename that file, even though everyone is allowed to create files there. The classic case is slash-tmp: anyone can drop files in it, but you can't delete somebody else's. In ls dash-l it shows as a lowercase t at the very end, and you'll see slash-tmp listed as d-r-w-x-r-w-x-r-w-t.

To set these numerically, you prefix the usual three permission digits with one more: four for SUID, two for SGID, one for sticky. So chmod one-seven-seven-seven on slash-tmp sets the sticky bit, and chmod two-seven-seven-five on a project directory sets SGID.
